05217nam a22009015i 9783110306484DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2014    gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831103064847 a10.1515/97831103064842doi  a(DE-B1597)206980  a(OCoLC)881289220  a(OCoLC)961564880  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aPHI0160002bisacsh1 aFugate, Courtney D., eauthor.14aThe Teleology of Reason :bA Study of the Structure of Kant's Critical Philosophy /cCourtney D. Fugate. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (449 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aKantstudien-Ergänzungshefte ;v17800t Frontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tAbbreviations and the Use of Translations -- tPart I: Preliminary Investigations -- tChapter 1 Motivations -- tChapter 2 Teleology: Rudiments of a Theory -- tPart II: The Teleology of Human Knowledge -- tChapter 3 The Historical Roots of Kant's Concept of Experience -- tChapter 4 Teleology in the Transcendental Aesthetic and Analytic -- tChapter 5 Teleology in the Transcendental Dialectic -- tPart III: The Teleology of Freedom -- tIntroduction to Part III -- tChapter 6 The Teleology of Freedom: The Structure of Moral Self-Consciousness in the Analytic -- tChapter 7 Kant on Rational Faith as an Expression of Autonomy -- tChapter 8 The Teleological Unity of Reason and Kant's Idea of Philosophy -- tBibliography -- tRegister0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis work argues that teleological motives lie at the heart of Kant's critical philosophy and that a precise analysis of teleological structures can both illuminate the basic strategy of its fundamental arguments and provide a key to understanding its unity. It thus aims, through an examination of each of Kant's major writings, to provide a detailed interpretation of his claim that philosophy in the true sense must consist of a teleologia rationis humanae.The author argues that Kant's critical philosophy forged a new link between traditional teleological concepts and the basic structure of rationality, one that would later inform the dynamic conception of reason at the heart of German Idealism. The process by which this was accomplished began with Kant's development of a uniquely teleological conception of systematic unity already in the precritical period. The individual chapters of this work attempt to show how Kant adapted and refined this conception of systematic unity so that it came to form the structural basis for the critical philosophy.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 4aKant, Immanuel. 4aTeleologie. 4aVernunft. 4areason. 4ateleology. 70(DE-601)1054375730(DE-588)4165789-5aKritizismus2gnd 70(DE-601)1061437430(DE-588)4059367-8aTeleologie2gnd 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1z978311023857008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Philosophy English Language 2000-2014z978311023848808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Philosophy 2000 - 2014z9783110636949oZDB-23-GPH08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Complete Package 2014z9783110369526oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2014z9783110370393oZDB-23-DPH0 cEPUBz97831103679110 cprintz978311030626240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110306484423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110306484.jpg  a978-3-11-023848-8  DGBA Backlist Philosophy English Language 2000-2014c2000d2014  aDGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014c2000d2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS